isual scene generator**, and presented through a strong **interactive UI / analysis layer**.\ndocs/milestones.md:33:- **Grant** owns the wave model, discretization choices, coupling assumptions, stability reasoning, and validation logic  \ndocs/milestones.md:38:  - synapse coupling API  \ndocs/milestones.md:65:- define operators and coupling  \ndocs/milestones.md:78:- interpret baseline vs wave differences  \ndocs/milestones.md:93:| 7 | Map synapses and define inter-neuron coupling | Shared leaning math-physics (45/55) | Shared lead | Patch-level coupling model |\ndocs/milestones.md:95:| 9 | Build the baseline non-wave simulator | Programming-heavy (70/30) | Jack lead | Control model for comparison |\ndocs/milestones.md:97:| 11 | Add hybrid morphology classes | Shared leaning programming (60/40) | Jack lead | Surface / skeleton / point neuron mix |\ndocs/milestones.md:101:| 15 | Build experiment orchestration and ablations | Programming-heavy (80/20) | Jack lead | Batch runs, manifests, comparisons |\ndocs/milestones.md:123:**In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.**\ndocs/milestones.md:130:* surface-localized inputs on explicit T4/T5 morphology regions  \ndocs/milestones.md:131:* surface propagation over a morphology graph  \ndocs/milestones.md:133:* a shared downstream readout so comparison to baselines stays fair\ndocs/milestones.md:140:* a decoder or readout unavailable to the baselines  \ndocs/milestones.md:145:* **`P0`**: canonical point baseline using passive leaky linear non-spiking single-compartment neurons matched to the same circuit and readout  \ndocs/milestones.md:146:* **`P1`**: stronger reduced baseline using an effective-point or reduced-compartment model with explicit synaptic integration current or explicit delay structure\ndocs/milestones.md:151: In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\ndocs/milestones.md:153:**What should the wave model do differently than a baseline point-neuron model?**  \ndocs/milestones.md:154: It should add distributed, morphology-bound intraneuronal state and nothing else that can trivially explain the result.\ndocs/milestones.md:157: A geometry-sensitive shared-output effect, preferably on null-direction suppression or response latency, that survives a stronger reduced baseline.\ndocs/milestones.md:173:* **Strong:** the shared-readout change shrinks or disappears when morphology or synapse topology is shuffled  \ndocs/milestones.md:174:* **Very strong:** the effect survives the stronger reduced baseline `P1`\ndocs/milestones.md:179:2. **`10–25 s`**: split screen with matched point baseline on the left and surface model on the right for the same T4/T5-centered circuit  \ndocs/milestones.md:187:* split view showing baseline scalar activity versus surface-state activity on morphology  \ndocs/milestones.md:192:* `P0` versus `P1` challenge-baseline comparison plot  \ndocs/milestones.md:208:* creating the experiment manifest schema  \ndocs/milestones.md:229:* `P0` and `P1` baseline definitions are explicit  \ndocs/milestones.md:242:3. survival against a stronger reduced baseline  \ndocs/milestones.md:329:* root ID manifests for active, candidate, and context graphs  \ndocs/milestones.md:341:* there is a named manifest for the locked boundary  \ndocs/milestones.md:342:* every active neuron has a role label and fidelity class  \ndocs/milestones.md:345:* both of you can explain why this boundary is sufficient for the first morphology-sensitive test  \ndocs/milestones.md:381:- manifest validation  \ndocs/milestones.md:386:- flagging missing metadata needed for later coupling